1. Observability & Reliability in CI/CD Pipelines
    - Observability and reliability ensure your pipeline is transparent, predictable, and resilient. In other words, you want to know what’s happening, detect issues early, and recover automatically from failures.

2. Pipeline Monitoring
    - Definition: Keeping an eye on your CI/CD pipeline to detect failures, slow builds, or other anomalies.
    - Implementation: Trigger notifications when something goes wrong.
    - Tools: Slack, Email, Teams, PagerDuty, or custom dashboards.
    - Example in a Node.js pipeline using GitHub Actions:
        name: Node.js CI
        on: [push, pull_request]
        jobs:
            build-and-test:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                steps:
                    - uses: actions/checkout@v3
                    - name: Setup Node.js
                        uses: actions/setup-node@v3
                        with:
                        node-version: 18
                    - run: npm install
                    - run: npm test
                # Send notifications on failure
                # Slack webhook example
                notifications:
                slack:
                    webhook_url: ${{ secrets.SLACK_WEBHOOK }}
                    on_failure: true
    - Explanation:
        - If a build or test fails, a Slack message is sent to your team immediately. This improves observability, so you know the health of your pipeline in real time.

3. Retry Strategies for Flaky Builds
    - Definition: Some builds fail intermittently due to external dependencies, network issues, or timing problems. Instead of failing immediately, retry the job a few times.
    - Implementation: Configure the CI/CD tool to retry failed jobs automatically.
    - Example in GitHub Actions:
        jobs:
            build:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                strategy:
                    fail-fast: false
                    matrix:
                        attempt: [1, 2, 3] # retry 3 times
                steps:
                    - uses: actions/checkout@v3
                    - name: Setup Node.js
                        uses: actions/setup-node@v3
                        with:
                            node-version: 18
                    - run: npm install
                    - run: npm test
    - Explanation: 
        - If the test fails due to a temporary network issue or flaky test, the pipeline will retry up to 3 times before finally reporting failure. This increases pipeline reliability.

4. Metrics: Build Duration, Failure Rates, Test Coverage Trends:
    - Definition: Collect and analyze metrics to track pipeline performance over time.
        - Build Duration: How long does it take to build and test your app?
        - Failure Rates: How often does the pipeline fail?
        - Test Coverage Trends: How is your code coverage changing over time?
    - Tools: GitHub Actions + Codecov, Jenkins, CircleCI Insights, Grafana dashboards.
    - Node.js Example (with Codecov for coverage metrics):
        jobs:
            test-and-report:
                runs-on: ubuntu-latest
                steps:
                - uses: actions/checkout@v3
                - uses: actions/setup-node@v3
                    with:
                        node-version: 18
                - run: npm install
                - run: npm test -- --coverage
                - name: Upload coverage to Codecov
                    uses: codecov/codecov-action@v3
                    with:
                        token: ${{ secrets.CODECOV_TOKEN }}
    - Explanation:
        - npm test -- --coverage generates coverage metrics for your Node.js app.
        - Codecov action uploads it to Codecov dashboards, allowing you to visualize trends over time.
    - You can also track average build time and failure rate in GitHub Actions Insights or other CI dashboards to monitor pipeline health.

